 social construction, post-colonialism, and gendered lenses from an interdisciplinary perspective. This combination showcases in particular the political implications of identity, how it is constituted, and the effects it produces. This edited collection will be of particular interest to students of international relations theory, migration studies, gender and sexuality, post-colonialism and policy-making at both undergraduate and postgraduate levels.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCitizenship. 0aCultural pluralism. 0aEthnic groupsxCivil rights. 0aGroup identityxPolitical aspects. 0aGroup identityxSocial aspects. 0aIdentity (Psychology)xSocial aspects. 0aIdentity politics. 0aImmigrantsxCivil rights. 0aMinoritiesxCivil rights. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aBelonging.  aExclusion.  aIdentity.  aNational identity.  aPolitics.1 aAgius, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgius, Christine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArmillei, Riccardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerents, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergman Rosamond, Annika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhandour, Hind, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeep, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeep, Dean, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKramer, Paul Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinnane, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMudaliar, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator